  "footnotes": [
    "Văn Lang and Âu Lạc: the legendary Hùng kings of Văn Lang represent Vietnam's foundational mythology; Âu Lạc under An Dương Vương merged the Lạc Việt and Âu Việt peoples; archaeological evidence (Đông Sơn bronze drums) confirms a sophisticated Bronze Age civilization in the Red River delta",
    "Nam Việt (204–111 BCE): founded by Zhao Tuo (Triệu Đà), a Qin dynasty general; the kingdom straddled modern Guangdong/Guangxi and northern Vietnam; whether it was 'Chinese' or 'Vietnamese' remains a sensitive historiographic question; Han conquest in 111 BCE began over a millennium of Chinese rule",
    "Champa (c.192–1832): an Austronesian Indianized kingdom along the central Vietnamese coast; its people spoke Cham (Malayo-Polynesian, not Sino-Tibetan); Mỹ Sơn temple complex rivals Angkor in significance; Champa was gradually conquered through Vietnamese 'Nam tiến' (southward advance) — the final remnant was absorbed by the Nguyễn in 1832",
    "Đại Việt independence (938): Ngô Quyền's victory over the Southern Han at the Battle of Bạch Đằng River ended over 1,000 years of Chinese domination; the Lý dynasty (1009–1225) consolidated the independent state with a centralized administration modeled on Chinese institutions but distinctly Vietnamese in character",
    "Trịnh-Nguyễn partition (1545–1787): Vietnam was effectively divided between the Trịnh lords (controlling the Lê emperor in Hanoi) and the Nguyễn lords (ruling from Huế southward); the Nguyễn continued the Nam tiến, absorbing Champa remnants and Khmer territories in the Mekong delta — creating the modern Vietnamese territorial shape",
    "Tây Sơn dynasty (1778–1802): the three Tây Sơn brothers overthrew both the Trịnh and Nguyễn lords and briefly unified Vietnam; Quang Trung (Nguyễn Huệ) defeated a Qing Chinese invasion in 1789; the dynasty collapsed after his death, and Nguyễn Ánh reunified Vietnam as Emperor Gia Long in 1802",
    "French Indochina (1887–1945): France divided Vietnam into three parts — Cochinchina (direct colony), Annam (protectorate with puppet emperor), and Tonkin (protectorate) — combined with Laos and Cambodia into the Indochinese Union; this tripartite division reflected and deepened regional differences that persist today"
  ]
